## Verdict: CONCERN

### 1. [medium] The circuit breaker does not fully fast-fail once another worker opens it
Refs: [src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3539), [src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3548), [src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3578), [src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/pr9_embed_watchdog.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/pr9_embed_watchdog.rs:238)

`embed_circuit_open` is checked only once at `run_projection_job` entry. A job already inside the retry loop can keep sleeping, reacquiring `embed_serialize`, and spawning more timed-out watchdog threads even after another worker has latched the breaker. That means the leak is bounded, but not by the advertised threshold alone, and "fail fast" is not true for already-started jobs.

The new breaker test masks this by forcing `set_projection_retry_delays_for_test(&[])`, so it never exercises the default retry path (`[1000, 4000, 16000]`) where post-latch extra attempts are possible. I would re-check `embed_circuit_open` before each retry attempt, and again just before spawning the next watchdog thread.

### 2. [low] The updated serialization rationale is still not internally consistent in comments
Refs: [src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:197), [src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3561), [src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3499)

The field-level doc on `embed_serialize` is mostly corrected: safety-first, throughput-neutral, old "~13x" claim withdrawn. But the hot-path comment at `run_projection_job` still says serialization "avoids the CPU-oversubscription throughput collapse", and `embed_with_watchdog` still says no engine-side serialization lock is held during embed, which is no longer true after `embed_serialize`.

That is documentation drift, not a code-path bug, but it means the rationale is not fully cleaned up yet.

**What passed on inspection**

- The breaker does improve the original timeout-path leak materially: fresh jobs do fail immediately once `embed_circuit_open` is observed, so the abandoned-thread growth is no longer one-per-doc.
- Reset placement is sensible for the leak-bounding goal: `Ok` and typed `Failed` clear the consecutive-timeout streak; timeout increments it; a panic still routes through `resume_unwind` into the existing EU-5f batch `catch_unwind` path.
- `embed_serialize` plus watchdog still preserves the prior accepted trade-off: strict serialization is relaxed only on timeout, commit/cursor logic remains unchanged, and single-writer / projection-cursor freshness still look preserved.
- Session-latched breaker behavior looks acceptable to me as a conservative availability tradeoff for this slice. It is operationally blunt, but not a correctness concern by itself.

**Reviewer process notes**

- Reviewed the requested `lib.rs` diff, all four PR-9 tests, the prior CONCERN writeup, and ADR-0.6.0 Invariants 4 and 5.
- Could not run tests in this read-only sandbox, so this is source review only.
- Repo-local `MEMORY.md` / `feedback_*.md` were not present under `fathomdb`; the only `MEMORY.md` reachable from `..` belonged to a different project, so I did not treat it as authoritative for this review.
